—’Щ@0fdf62629f15ec84d4766d67db5c7c826f22db445e8fd4de6657b347de7b704bЪ!Title: Moving Around the System
Path: Moving Around the System
Content:
A defining characteristic of a shell is the ability to navigate and interact with the filesystem. Nushell is, of course, no exception. Here are some common commands you might use when interacting with the filesystem:
’Щ@3bdf6fb9d8d3f70206317ace893d610ca67cc4fdf360e1992b79d7fd2cde9779ЪұTitle: Moving Around the System
Path: Viewing Directory Contents
Content:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
ls

```
As seen in the Quick Tour, the 
[link: /commands/docs/ls.md] ``ls``
 command returns the contents of a directory. Nushell's 
``ls``
 will return the contents as a 
[link: types_of_data.html#tables] table
.
The 
[link: /commands/docs/ls.md] ``ls``
 command also takes an optional argument to change what you'd like to view. For example, we can list the files that end in ".md"
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
ls *.md
# => в•ӯв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•®
# => в”Ӯ # в”Ӯ        name        в”Ӯ type в”Ӯ   size   в”Ӯ   modified   в”Ӯ
# => в”ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”јв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”јв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”јв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”јв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Ө
# => в”Ӯ 0 в”Ӯ CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ  3.4 KiB в”Ӯ 9 months ago в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 1 в”Ӯ CONTRIBUTING.md    в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ 11.0 KiB в”Ӯ 5 months ago в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 2 в”Ӯ README.md          в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ 12.0 KiB в”Ӯ 6 days ago   в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 3 в”Ӯ SECURITY.md        в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ  2.6 KiB в”Ӯ 2 months ago в”Ӯ
# => в•°в”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•Ҝ

```
’Щ@27396a156cbe74b7a306e1aa3913510505c7f12c09486c7c51b239eabbd18183ЪЎTitle: Moving Around the System
Path: Glob Patterns (wildcards)
Content:
The asterisk (
``*``
) in the above optional argument 
``*.md``
 is sometimes called a wildcard or a glob. It lets us match anything. You can read this glob 
``*.md``
 as 
"match any filename, so long as it ends with '.md'."
The most general glob is 
``*``
, which will match all paths. More often, you'll see this pattern used as part of another pattern, for example 
``*.bak``
 and 
``temp*``
.
Nushell also supports a double 
``*``
 which will traverse paths that are nested inside of other directories. For example, 
``ls **/*``
 will list all the non-hidden paths nested under the current directory.
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
ls **/*.md
# => в•ӯв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”¬в”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•®
# => в”Ӯ # в”Ӯ             name              в”Ӯ type в”Ӯ   size   в”Ӯ   modified   в”Ӯ
# => в”ңв”Җв”Җв”Җв”јв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”јв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”јв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”јв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Ө
# => в”Ӯ 0 в”Ӯ CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md            в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ  3.4 KiB в”Ӯ 5 months ago в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 1 в”Ӯ CONTRIBUTING.md               в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ 11.0 KiB в”Ӯ a month ago  в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 2 в”Ӯ README.md                     в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ 12.0 KiB в”Ӯ a month ago  в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 3 в”Ӯ SECURITY.md                   в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ  2.6 KiB в”Ӯ 5 hours ago  в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 4 в”Ӯ benches/README.md             в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ    249 B в”Ӯ 2 months ago в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 5 в”Ӯ crates/README.md              в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ    795 B в”Ӯ 5 months ago в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 6 в”Ӯ crates/nu-cli/README.md       в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ    388 B в”Ӯ 5 hours ago  в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 7 в”Ӯ crates/nu-cmd-base/README.md  в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ    262 B в”Ӯ 5 hours ago  в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 8 в”Ӯ crates/nu-cmd-extra/README.md в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ    669 B в”Ӯ 2 months ago в”Ӯ
# => в”Ӯ 9 в”Ӯ crates/nu-cmd-lang/README.md  в”Ӯ file в”Ӯ  1.5 KiB в”Ӯ a month ago  в”Ӯ
# => в•°в”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”ҙв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв”Җв•Ҝ

```
Here, we're looking for any file that ends with ".md". The double-asterisks further specify 
"in any directory starting from here."
Nushell's globbing syntax not only supports 
``*``
, but also matching 
[link: https://docs.rs/nu-glob/latest/nu_glob/struct.Pattern.html] single characters with 
``?``
 and character groups with 
``[...]``
.
Escaping the 
``*``
, 
``?``
, and 
``[]``
 patterns works by enclosing them in a single-quoted, double-quoted, or

[link: working_with_strings.md#raw-strings] raw string
. For example, to show the contents of a directory named

``[slug]``
, use 
``ls "[slug]"``
 or 
``ls '[slug]'``
.
However, 
backtick
 quoted strings do not escape globs. For example, compare the following scenarios:
Unquoted: Glob pattern
An unquoted 
[link: working_with_strings.html#bare-word-strings] bare word string
 with glob characters is interpreted as a glob pattern, so the following will remove all files in the current directory that contain

``myfile``
 as any part of the filename:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
rm *myfile*

```
Quoted: String literal with asterisks
When quoting with single or double quotes, or using a 
[link: working_with_strings.html#raw-strings] raw string
, a 
string
 with the literal, escaped asterisks (or other glob characters) is passed to the command. The result is not a glob. The following command will only remove a file literally named 
``*myfile*``
 (including the asterisks). Other files with 
``myfile``
 in the name are not affected:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
rm "*myfile*"

```
Backtick-quoted: Glob pattern
Asterisks (and other glob patterns) within a 
[link: working_with_strings.html#backtick-quoted-strings] backtick-quoted string
 are interpreted as a glob pattern. Notice that this is the same behavior as that of the bare-word string example in #1 above.
The following, as with that first example, removes all files in the current directory that contain 
``myfile``
 as part of the filename
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
rm `*myfile*`

```
::: tip

Nushell also includes a dedicated 
[link: https://www.nushell.sh/commands/docs/glob.html] ``glob``
 command
 with support for more complex globbing scenarios.

:::
’Щ@79d5ed67ae264d5ae4d187871f0b46fed26f1eb3f9f399f0e667d4ed81256be0ЪлTitle: Moving Around the System
Path: Converting Strings to Globs
Content:
The quoting techniques above are useful when constructing glob-literals, but you may need to construct globs programmatically. There are several techniques available for this purpose:
``into glob``
The 
[link: /commands/docs/into_glob.html] ``into glob``
 command
 can be used to convert a string (and other types) into a glob. For instance:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
# Find files whose name includes the current month in the form YYYY-mm

let current_month = (date now | format date '%Y-%m')

let glob_pattern = ($"*($current_month)*" | into glob)

ls $glob_pattern

```
The spread operator combined with the 
[link: /commands/docs/glob.html] ``glob``
 command
:
The 
[link: /commands/docs/glob.html] ``glob``
 command
 (note: not the same as 
``into glob``
) produces a 
[link: types_of_data.html#lists] ``list``
 of filenames that match the glob pattern. This list can be expanded and passed to filesystem commands using the 
[link: operators.html#spread-operator] spread operator
:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
# Find files whose name includes the current month in the form YYYY-mm

let current_month = (date now | format date '%Y-%m')

ls ...(glob $"*($current_month)*")

```
Force 
``glob``
 type via annotation:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
# Find files whose name includes the current month in the form YYYY-mm

let current_month = (date now | format date '%Y-%m')

let glob_pattern: glob = ($"*($current_month)*")

ls $glob_pattern

```
’Щ@7472b9b986535dc1a38b2cf40528723754c2649a2ae6640d8777f59a84140ff5ЪшTitle: Moving Around the System
Path: Creating a Directory
Content:
As with most other shells, the 
[link: /commands/docs/mkdir.md] ``mkdir``
 command
 is used to create new directories. One subtle difference is that Nushell's internal 
``mkdir``
 command operates like the Unix/Linux 
``mkdir -p``
 by default, in that it:
Will create multiple directory levels automatically. For example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
mkdir modules/my/new_module

```
This will create all three directories even if none of them currently exists. On Linux/Unix, this requires 
``mkdir -p``
.
Will not error if the directory already exists. For example:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
mkdir modules/my/new_module

mkdir modules/my/new_module

# => No error

```
::: tip

A common mistake when coming to Nushell is to attempt to use 
``mkdir -p <directory>``
 as in the native Linux/Unix version. However, this will generate an 
``Unknown Flag``
 error on Nushell.
Just repeat the command without the 
``-p``
 to achieve the same effect.

:::
’Щ@0aa772cec8de3c3e9b984ed3c8d80d8f60fe506cc96f4ca533144200a0c0c532ЪBTitle: Moving Around the System
Path: Changing the Current Directory
Content:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
cd cookbook

```
To change from the current directory to a new one, use the 
[link: /commands/docs/cd.md] ``cd``
 command.
Changing the current working directory can also be done if 
[link: /commands/docs/cd.md] ``cd``
 is omitted and a path by itself is given:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
cookbook/

```
Just as in other shells, you can use either the name of the directory, or if you want to go up a directory you can use the 
``..``
 shortcut.
You can also add additional dots to go up additional directory levels:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
# Change to the parent directory
cd ..
# or
..
# Go up two levels (parent's parent)
cd ...
# or
...
# Go up three levels (parent of parent's parent)
cd ....
# Etc.

```
::: tip

Multi-dot shortcuts are available to both internal Nushell 
[link: /commands/categories/filesystem.html] filesystem commands
 as well as to external commands. For example, running 
``^stat ....``
 on a Linux/Unix system will show that the path is expanded to 
``../../..``

:::
You can combine relative directory levels with directory names as well:
```Fenced(Borrowed("nu"))
cd ../sibling

```
::: tip IMPORTANT TIP

Changing the directory with 
[link: /commands/docs/cd.md] ``cd``
 changes the 
``PWD``
 environment variable. This means that a change of a directory is kept to the current scope (e.g. block or closure). Once you exit the block, you'll return to the previous directory. You can learn more about this in the 
[link: ./environment.md] Environment
 chapter.

:::
’Щ@643129d191347e945f3cdce8778a6de50576e437f76915cd7f3c4db41dbca30eЪҲTitle: Moving Around the System
Path: Filesystem Commands
Content:
Nu also provides some basic 
[link: /commands/categories/filesystem.html] filesystem commands
 that work cross-platform such as:
[link: /commands/docs/mv.md] ``mv``
 to rename or move a file or directory to a new location
[link: /commands/docs/cp.md] ``cp``
 to copy an item to a new location
[link: /commands/docs/rm.md] ``rm``
 to remove items from the filesystem
::: tip NOTE

Under Bash and many other shells, most filesystem commands (other than 
``cd``
) are actually separate binaries in the system. For instance, on a Linux system, 
``cp``
 is the 
``/usr/bin/cp``
 binary. In Nushell, these commands are built-in. This has several advantages:
They work consistently on platforms where a binary version may not be available (e.g. Windows). This allows the creation of cross-platform scripts, modules, and custom commands.
They are more tightly integrated with Nushell, allowing them to understand Nushell types and other constructs
As mentioned in the 
[link: quick_tour.html] Quick Tour
, they are documented in the Nushell help system. Running 
``help <command>``
 or 
``<command> --help``
 will display the Nushell documentation for the command.
While the use of the Nushell built-in versions is typically recommended, it is possible to access the Linux binaries. See 
[link: ./running_externals.md] Running System Commands
 for details.
